[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Exploring class initialization**\n\nI'm considering if the class initialization could happen during the image build if H2 is initialized. There might be a risk of failure due to no class present. I wonder if I could avoid using the Gradle property by setting it in the test class. \n\nMaybe I should add a test class name alphabetically before H2Test? JUnit does discovery based on class name order, but that’s not guaranteed. Renaming to \"AJdbcUtilsTest\" could help, but there’s a dedicated class for JdbcUtils that should stay as JdbcUtilsTest. \n\nIt seems better to set the system property globally in build.gradle, which makes things consistent. Making sure H2 operations are serialized correctly is essential too, especially when dealing with JAVA_OBJECT. I might need to implement a custom serializer and manage the reflection configuration as well.\n\n**Reviewing agent run and H2Test**\n\nI'm considering how the agent runs the JVM with H2Test first. It generates dynamic access from clinit and wonders if the user-code filter excludes the helper. Since the caller is org.h2, that could impact things. To be cautious, I think I should add a reflect-config for the h2.JdbcUtilsTest$PassThroughJavaObjectSerializer constructors. However, since there's no tests-only reflect config for native, I’ll need to add one to ensure everything works smoothly. It feels like I’m covering all bases!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0436d349b38d0e700169f1000e4500819386edac8ff2644c2a\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp8QAehHSRi1WEA7KqnobBKYGKUGrk3opZfZCReeIx9ochgMe5x0ViIClNqZ_f8X8JX3-hU_reApMfv-L1dOcu8e-6aAuQV7-x0mRQiLU0bfbT71Wbe88a3yvHOsBgSA5Rh0KGmX7oZuOUkRKtOAQ5uQcyZ_hzz7HV0qefPCUwl7jCI4yXuT9etCXg00WSYamXtPVsD8FPH9mkssR0SkYXwiFthOJd2cDon3yBlb8nDoUr8XMd-fW2bL-UDrOdHPeSbxhMpnTGYmHkPxpD00P0nSXn4QXYTmGdq5kmLbLouKltmIp_qcY6CwPgfc4TWkpivGrG_lDX-bL95Grob9i5IJY-6Iu9